    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and the principal isnt going down as much as i thought it would even though i pay the same amount every month. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated on a declining balance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Interest is calculated monthly based on the remaining principal balance, so as you make payments, less interest accrues each subsequent month. However, since you are making a fixed dollar amount of payment, the portion covering interest decreases only gradually at first, meaning more of your payment covers principal over time only as the interest balance shrinks. This means your principal balance drops slowly in the early years of the loan because the interest charge \"eats up\" most of your fixed monthly payment until the balance becomes small enough that your payment exceeds the interest cost.",
