    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i guess that makes sense. it just feels so much like there are these hidden things eating away at my money before it even hits the debt. like, if there were ways to explain it more simply, what's the actual \"invisible\" part of the math that makes it so frustrating?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The most \"invisible\" factor is often how interest compounds or how the loan amortization schedule allocates your first few payments, where maybe 80-90% goes to interest with only a tiny slice reducing the debt. This creates a false expectation that a standard payment will significantly shrink your balance, leading to the frustration of seeing slow progress. Since institutions follow this same standard math for every loan, there is no secret tactic they can use to hide or sabotage your payments, though the formula does naturally slow your progress in the early years.\n</think>\n\nThe most \"invisible\" factor is often how interest compounds or how the loan amortization schedule allocates your first few payments, where maybe 80-90% goes to interest with only a tiny slice reducing the debt. This creates a false expectation that a standard payment will significantly shrink your balance, leading to the frustration of seeing slow progress. Since institutions follow this same standard math for every loan, there is no secret tactic they can use to hide or sabotage your payments, though the formula does naturally slow your progress in the early years.",
